Iterative version in C++, left adjusted when printed.

---
In this program a palindrome is determined without
regard to any capitalization.  Thus, for example,
both "Otto" and "otto" are palindomes.

A lot of the work of the program goes into discarding
repetitive palindrones.  In the file

   /usr/dict/words

each word is unique, but in most text files not all the
palindromes will be unique.  For example, in a large
English text file the palindrome "a" can be
expected to occur many times.

The algorithm that determines a word is not obvious.
Look in the function action::get_palindromes()
to see the algorithm that gets used.
I tried other algorithms.

The palindromes are left adjusted when printed.
